      "target": {
        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "feat(cron): on-exit schedule — wake on a watched command's exit",
        "body": "## Summary\n\nAdds an **`on-exit` cron schedule kind**: a job that fires once when a watched shell command exits, starting a fresh agent turn in the originating conversation. It's \"a #83738 cron wake, triggered by a process exit instead of by the tool call\" — it reuses the merged origin-aware wake as its delivery mechanism and only adds the *trigger*.\n\n- **The gap.** openclaw already wakes the parent when an *openclaw-managed* child finishes — sub-agents, isolated cron runs, and image/video/music generation raise `task_completion` internal events consumed by the embedded-agent runtime. But nothing watches an **arbitrary external command**, and the CLI backends can't participate in that internal system at all: a command a `claude-cli` agent runs via its exec tool lives inside the per-turn process tree that's `signalProcessTree(SIGTERM→SIGKILL)`'d at turn end (#71662), so it dies before it can observe an exit or fire a wake. The only pre-existing workaround is a polling `every:Nm` cron that burns a turn per poll.\n- **What this does.** A new `CronSchedule` kind `{ kind: \"on-exit\", command, cwd? }`, executed by a **gateway-ProcessSupervisor-owned watcher** (`cron-exit-watchers.ts`). The watcher runs the command as a child of the *gateway* supervisor — outside any agent turn's process tree — so it survives turn teardown by construction. On exit it fires #83738's origin-aware wake on the job's captured session, so the woken turn **continues the originating conversation** (native `claude-cli --resume`, see proof), with the exit code folded into the woken turn's text. One-shot per arm.\n- **Surfaces.** `on-exit` is accepted by the protocol schema, the cron tool (`schedule.kind:\"on-exit\"` + `command`/`cwd`), and the CLI (`cron add --on-exit <shell> [--on-exit-cwd <path>]`). Watchers arm on job add/update and on gateway-startup reconcile (so persisted jobs re-arm after a restart) and cancel on remove/disable/shutdown.\n- **AI-assisted:** yes — drafted with Claude.\n\n## Why a *non*-internally-managed wake (and why it works for every backend)\n\nThe internal `task_completion` machinery is embedded-runtime-bound and command-agnostic — it has no \"watch a shell command\" task type, for any backend. A `claude-cli` (or `claude-cli-interactive`/proxy) agent can't register an external command with it, and a command it runs inline dies at turn teardown. So the watcher must live outside the turn and outside the embedded-agent event system — the gateway ProcessSupervisor. Because the wake then rides the gateway **command lane** (busy-detection is `getQueueSize(Main)`, acquired at the dispatch layer *above* the backend), it behaves identically on plain `claude-cli` and the interactive MITM backend: if the watched command exits mid-turn, the wake hits `requests-in-flight`, re-queues, and fires when the lane frees — never concurrently. Proven below on plain `claude-cli`; the interactive path is the same lane mechanism.\n\n## Real behavior proof\n\nReal OpenClaw gateway (built from this branch) + real `claude-cli` (claude-sonnet-4-6) backend with native session resume (`resumeArgs`), in a Linux container. A persisted `on-exit` job (`command: \"sleep 22\"`) is loaded at gateway startup; a binding turn establishes the session; the watched command exits; the watcher fires the origin wake. Gateway logs ([gw-clean.log](https://github.com/anagnorisis2peripeteia/openclaw/blob/proof-assets-onexit/gw-clean.log), [cron-exit-structured.log](https://github.com/anagnorisis2peripeteia/openclaw/blob/proof-assets-onexit/cron-exit-structured.log)):\n\n```\n20:45:02  cron-exit: watcher armed                          jobId=onexit-hl command=\"sleep 22\"   <- armed from the PERSISTED job at startup (survives restart)\n20:45:12  cli exec  trigger=heartbeat  useResume=false      <- binding turn establishes the cli session\n20:45:17  (binding turn finished)\n20:45:27  cron-exit: watched command exited; firing job     exitCode=0 reason=exit                <- watched command exits -> watcher fires the origin wake\n20:45:46  cli exec  trigger=heartbeat  useResume=true  resumeSession=1b22992cb50d  reuse=reusable  historyPrompt=present\n                                                             ^- the woken turn NATIVELY --resumes the originating session (not history-replay)\n```\n\nThe wake turn ran *after* the binding turn finished, so it is unambiguously the on-exit wake — and it natively `--resume`d the binding turn's claude-cli session, continuing the conversation. A separate run also exercised the **mid-turn case**: the watched command exited while a turn was in flight, the wake hit `requests-in-flight`, re-queued, and the woken turn ran after the in-flight turn ended (never concurrently).\n\n- **Behavior or issue addressed:** an agent (any backend, esp. `claude-cli`) cannot reliably arm \"wake me when this external command exits\" — managed `task_completion` doesn't cover external commands and an agent-spawned command dies at turn teardown.\n- **Real environment tested:** real gateway from this branch + real `claude-cli` backend with `resumeArgs`, Linux container; on-exit job persisted to the store and armed at startup.\n- **Exact steps:** seed a persisted `on-exit` job (`sleep 22`, sessionKey bound), start the gateway, run a binding turn, let the command exit.\n- **Evidence after fix:** redacted gateway logs above ([gw-clean.log](https://github.com/anagnorisis2peripeteia/openclaw/blob/proof-assets-onexit/gw-clean.log), [cron-exit-structured.log](https://github.com/anagnorisis2peripeteia/openclaw/blob/proof-assets-onexit/cron-exit-structured.log)) showing arm → exit → fire → native-resume woken turn.\n- **Observed result after fix:** the watcher armed from the persisted job, the watched command's exit fired the origin wake, and the woken turn natively `--resume`d the originating session.\n- **What was not tested live:** the Telegram-thread visual (the session is a local key here; thread delivery is #83738's merged + proven mechanism — the wake routing is identical regardless of channel). The interactive/MITM backend (same command-lane mechanism; not separately captured).\n\n### Bug caught by the live proof\n`getInvalidPersistedCronJobReason` only allowed `at/every/cron`, so on-exit jobs **failed persistence validation** — they couldn't be saved to the store or survive a restart (the watcher arms from the store at startup). Fixed + regression test. This is exactly the class of issue unit tests around the schema/codec missed and the live store-seed proof surfaced.\n\n## Tests / CI\n\n- New: `cron-exit-watchers.test.ts` (arm/fire-on-exit/skip-timer-and-disabled/idempotent/cancel/no-fire-after-cancel/one-shot), `persisted-shape.onexit.test.ts`, `schedule-options.onexit.test.ts` (CLI), `row-codec.schedule.test.ts` (store round-trip), plus on-exit cases in schedule/normalize.\n- tsgo clean; full cron suite + watcher/CLI suites green; full Linux unit suite run on this head (results in the re-review comment).\n",
